    {
      "id": "1a76adc5_a671d8a9",
      "file_path": "hv-collector-dcae-app-simulator/src/test/kotlin/org/onap/dcae/collectors/veshv/simulators/dcaeapp/impl/ConsumerTest.kt",
      "patchset_number": 8,
      "line": 47,
      "message": "1. OK\n2. Before should remain. Changing the order of tests can change the state (and fail the tests). Consumer is by definition a stateful class so we cannot do it. Or we can but it will be counter-intuitive for Spek newbies.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2683,
        "name": "Piotr Jaszczyk",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "piotr.jaszczyk@nokia.com",
        "username": "jaszczur"
      },
      "updated": "2018-08-30 06:44:43.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "1a76adc5_03ef5eea",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "1a76adc5_e6da704b",
      "file_path": "hv-collector-dcae-app-simulator/src/test/kotlin/org/onap/dcae/collectors/veshv/simulators/dcaeapp/impl/DcaeAppSimulatorTest.kt",
      "patchset_number": 8,
      "line": 99,
      "message": "Generally I agree. But using this style in class-level unit tests yields some problems:\n* As you've written - it requires us to do more work.\n* Having clean tests is very nice but it is more important in acceptance tests on component+ level. Class-scoped unit tests should be clean and easy to read but for developers. In other words: using suggested convention is very beneficial when writing executable specifications but not so much when writing unit tests.\n* It makes it very hard to use mocking. Mocks are statefull so each scenario should use fresh mocks. We can use Mockito.clearInvocations() but it is ugly, too. \"beforeEachTest\" is invoked before test blocks (that is \"is\" lambdas). So stubbing in \"given\" will yield exception.\n\nMy recommendation: let's leave it as is.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2683,
        "name": "Piotr Jaszczyk",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "piotr.jaszczyk@nokia.com",
        "username": "jaszczur"
      },
      "updated": "2018-08-30 06:44:43.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "1a76adc5_63941243",
      "unresolved": false
    },
